  "prompt": "How can I simplify [math]\\frac{1}{1+x^{m-n}}+ \\frac{1}{1+x^{n-m}}?[/math]",
  "response": "To simplify the expression \n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{1+x^{m-n}} + \\frac{1}{1+x^{n-m}},\n\\]\n\nwe first note that the terms \\(1+x^{m-n}\\) and \\(1+x^{n-m}\\) are closely related. Specifically, we observe that \\(1+x^{n-m} = 1 + \\frac{1}{x^{m-n}}\\) if we interpret \\(x^{n-m}\\) as the reciprocal of \\(x^{m-n}\\). \n\nTo facilitate the simplification, let \\(a = x^{m-n}\\). Then, we can rewrite the expression as:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{1+a} + \\frac{1}{1+\\frac{1}{a}}.\n\\]\n\nThe second term can be simplified further:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{1+\\frac{1}{a}} = \\frac{1}{\\frac{a+1}{a}} = \\frac{a}{a+1}.\n\\]\n\nNow, we can write the entire expression as:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{1+a} + \\frac{a}{a+1}.\n\\]\n\nThe common denominator for the two fractions is \\(1+a\\). We can write:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{1+a} + \\frac{a}{1+a} = \\frac{1 + a}{1 + a} = 1.\n\\]\n\nThus, the simplified form of \n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{1+x^{m-n}} + \\frac{1}{1+x^{n-m}}\n\\]\n\nis \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{1}.\n\\]",
